🤤🌮 - Tacos are a quintessential Mexican dish that has gained international acclaim for their versatility and vibrant flavors. Originating from the indigenous cultures of Mexico, tacos typically consist of a folded or rolled tortilla filled with various ingredients. The traditional taco uses a corn tortilla, though flour tortillas are also popular, especially in the northern regions of Mexico and in Tex-Mex cuisine. The fillings can range from seasoned meats like beef, pork, or chicken to vegetarian options such as beans, cheese, and vegetables. This adaptability makes tacos a favored choice for many people, accommodating a wide array of dietary preferences and tastes. One of the key aspects that makes tacos so enjoyable is their customizable nature. The basic structure of a taco allows for endless variations in fillings, toppings, and sauces. For instance, street tacos might be topped with simple ingredients like cilantro, onions, and a squeeze of lime, while more elaborate versions could include layers of salsa, guacamole, sour cream, and cheese. This customization is part of the appeal, allowing each person to tailor their taco to their specific liking. Additionally, tacos are often enjoyed with a variety of side dishes and condiments, such as salsa, pickled jalapeños, and Mexican crema, which further enhance their flavor profile. In recent years, tacos have transcended their traditional roots, becoming a global phenomenon. Restaurants around the world offer innovative takes on the classic taco, incorporating ingredients and cooking styles from various culinary traditions. This fusion approach has led to the creation of unique taco variations, such as Korean BBQ tacos or sushi tacos, reflecting a blend of cultural influences. The taco’s global popularity underscores its role not just as a staple of Mexican cuisine, but as a versatile and beloved dish that brings people together through shared meals and creative culinary exploration.

The Red flag 🚩🚩 I think there's been a massive online culture that perpetuates the idea that every slight inconvenience is a 'red flag' (a.k.a a warning sign about someone). That any and everything we don't like is a 'red flag', where there is no room for personal growth, self-reflection and accountability. I've noticed a lot of binary thinking where someone is either completely 100% the perfect person of our dreams or they're completely meaningless and not worth speaking to and everything they do is a 'red flag' so we don't associate with them. I think this way of thinking forgets that people are complex and filled with flaws, and relationships often involve holding each other accountable and helping each other grow into better people. Something that could seem like a 'red flag' to us, may not be to another, and sometimes a 'red flag' could actually be an orange flag, that could turn into red or green depending on that person's path and their work on themselves. Everyone may have something that another person feels is a 'red flag', and sometimes red flags are not permanent, they can change into green and vice versa. Basically, we are not fixed beings. This isn't to say that we should ignore signs of something that really doesn't seem right to us or that it is our duty to always support people to change or settle when we are uncomfortable, but to understand that personality is filled with nuance, different cultures, values and context. I think the intended purpose of the 'red flag' has been watererd down under the guise of 'empowerment' and 'self-love', when actually it's just anything that is a mild inconvenience these days. This isn't everyone, but something I've noticed becoming popular and I think that sometimes people often use the 'red flag' to avoid work that they actually need to do on themselves 🙏🏼 . . . . #psychology #redflag #toxic #relationships #psychologist #mentalhealth #socialmedia #millennials #genz #culture #wellbeing #friendship #judgement #Dclinpsy #traineeclinicalpsychologist #infographic #flag #therapy #partner #mentalhealthawareness #pride #education #gaslighting #online #diversity #young #art #selflove
